The proof uses the "coloring book" method described in the Goodman-Strauss & Sloane article. The subgraph H is shown above in the links.

The figure is divided into 6 sectors by the blue trunks. In the interior of each sector, working outwards from the base point P at the origin, there are successively 1,2,3,4,... (red) 12-gons. All the 12-gons (both red and blue) have a unique closest point to P.
If the closest point in a 12-gon is at distance d from P, then the contributions of the 12 points of the 12-gon to a(d), a(d+1), ..., a(d+6) are 1,2,2,2,2,2,1, respectively.
The rest of the proof is now a matter of simple counting.
The blue 12-gons (along the trunks) are especially easy to count, because there is a unique blue 12-gon at shortest distance d from P for d = 1,2,3,4,...

A072188.name: Numbers n such that n divides sigma(n-1)+sigma(n)+sigma(n+1), where sigma() is the "sum of integer divisors" function.

A072189.name: Weight distribution of [103,52,19] binary quadratic-residue (or QR) code.

A072190.name: Indices of primes with primitive root 2.

A072192.name: Indices of Sophie Germain primes: p and 2p+1 are primes.

A072193.name: Concatenate continued fraction expansions of the rational numbers 1/2, 1/3, 2/3, 1/4, 2/4, 3/4, 1/5, 2/5, ...

A072194.name: Replace all prime factors p of n with n-p.

A072195.name: Replace all prime factors p of n with n/p.

A072196.name: Multiples of 3 which on one operation of the Collatz function T (N -> 3N+1/2^r) yield the number 5.

A072198.name: E12 range of preferred resistor values in electronic engineering.

A072199.name: a(n)-th factorial is the smallest factorial containing exactly n 5's, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072200.name: a(n)-th factorial is the smallest factorial containing exactly n 6's, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072202.name: Same numbers of prime factors of forms 4*k+1 and 4*k+3, counted with multiplicity.

A072203.name: (Number of oddly factored numbers <= n) - (number of evenly factored numbers <= n).

A072204.name: a(n) is the smallest integer k whose factorial contains exactly n 7's, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072205.name: a(n) = (p^2 - p + 2)/2 for p = prime(n); number of squares modulo p^2.
formula: a(n) = A000124(A000040(n)) by definition [_Bert Seghers_, Jan 01 2012]

A072206.name: Third terms of triple Peano sequence A071988.
formula: Numbers, except 2, satisfy a(n) = 1 + k/3 * (4k^2+5), with k in A005097. - _Ralf Stephan_, Aug 21 2004
a(n) = (n^3+5*n+6)/6, for n+1 prime, so a(n) = A000125(A006093(n)) - Bert Seghers, Jan 01 2012, corrected by _Robert Israel_, Jun 20 2019

A072207.name: a(0) = 1; for n>0, a(n) = number of distinct sums of subsets of {1, 1/2, 1/3, 1/4, ..., 1/n} (allowing the empty subset).
formula: a(p) = 2 * a(p-1) for p prime. a(2*p) = 2 * a(2*p-1) for p>3 prime. - _Giovanni Resta_, Jul 18 2019

A072208.name: a(n)-th factorial is the smallest factorial containing exactly n 8's, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072209.name: Number of primitive roots of those integers with at least one primitive root.

A072211.name: a(n) = p-1 if n=p, p if n=p^e and e<>1, 1 otherwise; p a prime.
formula: a(n) = Product_{d divides n} phi(n/d)^mu(d). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 08 2004
a(n) = A217863(n)/A217863(n-1) for n > 1. - _Eric Desbiaux_, Nov 23 2012; corrected by _Thomas Ordowski_, Aug 25 2015
D.g.f.: zeta(s) + Sum_{p prime} (p-2+p^(-s))/(p^s-1), - _Robert Israel_, Aug 25 2015

A072212.name: Smallest m such that number of partitions of m exceeds 10^n.

A072214.name: Number of partitions of Fibonacci(n).
formula: Let P(i,j) denote the number of partitions of i whose highest term is j A072214(n) = A000041(F(n)) = P(F(n+2),F(n+1)) - Philippe LALLOUET (philip.lallouet(AT)wanadoo.fr), Sep 14 2007

A072215.name: a(0) = 4; for n >= 0, a(n+1) = number of partitions of a(n).

A072216.name: Consider the Reverse and Add! problem (cf. A001127); of all the n-digit numbers N which eventually reach a palindrome, pick that number N which takes the greatest number of steps to converge (in case of a tie, pick the smallest N); sequence gives values of N.

A072217.name: Consider the Reverse and Add! problem (cf. A001127); of all the n-digit numbers N which eventually reach a palindrome, pick that number N which takes the greatest number of steps to converge (in case of a tie, pick the smallest N); sequence gives number of steps N takes to converge.

A072218.name: Consider the Reverse and Add! problem (cf. A001127); of all the n-digit numbers N which eventually reach a palindrome, pick that number N which takes the greatest number of steps to converge (in case of a tie, pick the smallest N); sequence gives palindrome that is reached.

A072219.name: Any number n can be written uniquely in the form n = 2^k_1 - 2^k_2 + 2^k_3 - ... + 2^k_{2r+1} where the signs alternate, there are an odd number of terms, and k_1 > k_2 > k_3 > ... > k_{2r+1} >= 0; sequence gives number of terms 2r+1.

A072220.name: a(n)-th factorial is the smallest factorial containing exactly n 9's, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072221.name: a(n) = 6*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + 2, with a(0)=1, a(1)=4.
formula: a(n)=-1/2+(3/4)*((3+sqrt(8))^n+(3-sqrt(8))^n) for n>=0. a(n)=floor((3/4)*(3+sqrt(8))^n) for n>0. - _Franz Vrabec_, Aug 21 2006
a(n) = a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 25 2018

A072222.name: a(n) = mod(abs(n-1-a(n-2)),n) + mod(abs(n-1-a(n-1)),n-1), a(0) = 1, a(1) = 1.
formula: For n>6, a(n) = a(n-3) + 2 (conjectured). - _Ralf Stephan_, May 09 2004

A072223.name: Decimal expansion of unimodal analog of golden section with respect to A072176: a=lim A072176(n)/A072176(n+1).

A072224.name: Continued fraction expansion of constant A072223.

A072225.name: Numbers n such that prime(n) + prime(n+1) + prime(n+2) is prime.

A072226.name: Numbers n such that the n-th cyclotomic polynomial evaluated at 2  (=A019320(n)) is prime.

A072227.name: Numbers n such that reverse(d) divides reverse(n) for all divisors d of n.

A072228.name: Numbers n such that n = the sum of the reverses of the proper divisors of n.

A072229.name: Witt index of the standard bilinear form <1,1,1,...,1> over the 2-adic rationals.
formula: a(n) = 4 floor(n/7) + [0,0,0,0,1,2,3][n%7 + 1]. [Formula corrected by _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Apr 13 2009]

A072230.name: a(n) = n! (mod n^2), that is, n factorial modulo n^2.

A072231.name: a(n) = floor(n^2/A005185(n-1)), where A005185 is Hofstadter's Q-sequence.

A072233.name: Square array T(n,k) read by antidiagonals giving number of ways to distribute n indistinguishable objects in k indistinguishable containers; containers may be left empty.
formula: G.f. Product_{j=0..infinity} 1/(1-xy^j). Regarded as a triangular array, g.f. Product_{j=1..infinity} 1/(1-xy^j). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Dec 18 2006
O.g.f. of column No. k of the triangle a(n,k) is x^k/product(1-x^j,j=1..k), k>=0 (the undefined product for k=0 is put to 1). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Dec 03 2012

A072234.name: Numbers n such that reverse(n) = sum of the proper divisors of n.

A072235.name: Years of recorded observations of Comet Halley.

A072236.name: Numbers of primes between successive primorials.

A072239.name: a(0) = 11; a(n) = number of distinct partitions of the previous term.

A072241.name: Number of distinct partitions of Fibonacci(n).

A072243.name: Number of distinct partitions of n^2.

A072245.name: Smallest m such that number of distinct partitions of m exceeds 10^n.

A072246.name: Numbers which are simultaneously the number of partitions of some k and the number of distinct partitions of some m.

A072247.name: Triangle T(n,k) (n >= 2, 2 <= k <= n-1 if n > 2) giving number of non-crossing trees with n nodes and k endpoints.
formula: T(n, k) = U(n, k-1) - U(n, k) + binomial(n-1, k)*Sum_{j=0..k-1} binomial(n-1, j)*binomial(n-k-1, k-1-j)*2^(n-2*k+j)/(n-1) where U(n,k) = 2*binomial(n-2, k)*Sum_{j=0..k-1} binomial(n-1, j)*binomial(n-k-2, k-1-j)*2^(n-1-2*k+j)/(n-2) for 2 < k < n. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 06 2017

A072248.name: Triangle T(n,k) (n >= 2, 1 <= k <= n-1) giving number of non-crossing trees with n nodes and height k.
formula: Column g.f. are T(k) - T(k-1) (k = 1, 2, ...), where T(0) = z and T(k) = z/(1 - T(k-1)^2/z). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Dec 30 2004

A072250.name: Related to cyclotomic numbers of hypergraphs.

A072252.name: Numbers n for which one step of the Collatz iteration (3n+1)/2^r gives rise to values 41,35,29,23,17,11, and 5 for r=1,3,5,..,13.

A072253.name: Numbers n for which one step of the Collatz iteration (3n+1)/2^r gives rise to values 59,53,47,41,35,29,23,17,11 and 5 for r=1,3,5,..,19.

A072254.name: Numbers n such that triples generated by {2*(n-1),2*n,2*(n+1)} form A007534.

A072255.name: Number of ways to partition {1,2,...,n} into arithmetic progressions, where in each partition all the progressions have the same common difference and have lengths >= 2.
formula: a(n) = sum_{d=1}^{floor{n/2}} {{F_k}^r}*{F_{k-1}}^{d-r}, where d is the common difference of the arithmetic progressions, k = Floor{n/d}, r = n mod d and F_k is the k-th Fibonacci number (A000045). - Marty Getz (ffmpg1(AT)uaf.edu) and Dixon Jones (fndjj(AT)uaf.edu), May 21 2005

A072256.name: a(n) = 10*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n > 1, a(0) = a(1) = 1.
formula: a(n) = U(n-1, 5)-U(n-2, 5) = T(2*n-1, sqrt(3))/sqrt(3) with Chebyshev's U- and T- polynomials and U(-1, x) := 0, U(-2, x) := -1, T(-1, x) := x.
For all members x of the sequence, 6*x^2 - 2 is a square. Lim_{n->infinity} a(n)/a(n-1) = 5 + 2*sqrt(6). - _Gregory V. Richardson_, Oct 10 2002
Let q(n, x) = Sum_{i=0..n} x^(n-i)*binomial(2*n-i, i); then q(n, 8) = a(n+1). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 10 2002

A072263.name: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 5*a(n-2), with a(0)=2, a(1)=3.
formula: G.f.: G(0), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(29*k-9)/(x*(29*k+20) - 6/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 17 2013

A072264.name: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 5*a(n-2), with a(0)=1, a(1)=1.
formula: G.f.: G(0)*(1-2*x)/(2-3*x), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(29*k-9)/(x*(29*k+20) - 6/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 17 2013

A072265.name: Variant of Lucas numbers: a(n) = a(n-1) + 4*a(n-2) starting with a(0)=2 and a(1)=1.
formula: a(n) = [x^n] ( (1 + x + sqrt(1 + 2*x + 17*x^2))/2 )^n for n >= 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jun 23 2015

A072266.name: Number of words of length 2n generated by the two letters s and t that reduce to the identity 1 using the relations sssssss=1, tt=1 and stst=1. The generators s and t along with the three relations generate the 14-element dihedral group D7.

A072268.name: a(0)=1; a(n+1) = 1 + f(a(n))^2, where f(x) is the largest prime factor of x (A006530).

A072270.name: A partial product representation of A006131 and A072265.
formula: Let h=(1+sqrt(17))/2, Phi(n, x) = n-th cyclotomic polynomial, so x^n-1= product_{d|n} Phi(d, x), and let g(d) be the order of Phi(d, x). Then a(n)=(h-1)^g(n)*Phi(n, h^2/4), n>2.
a(p) = L(p) for odd prime p.
a(2p) = f(p) for odd prime p.
L(n) = product_{d|n} a(d) for odd n.
L(n*2^k) = product_{d|n} a(d*2^(k+1)) for k>0 and odd n.

A072271.name: A partial product representation of f(n) = A015523(n) and L(n) = A072263(n).
formula: Let h = (3+sqrt(29))/2, K(n, x) = n-th cyclotomic polynomial, so that x^n - 1 = Product_{d|n} K(d, x); g(d) is the order of K(d, x).

A072272.name: Number of active cells in n-th stage of growth of two-dimensional cellular automaton defined by "Rule 614", based on the 5-celled von Neumann neighborhood.

A072273.name: Index of powers of 2 that equal the number of noncongruent roots to the congruence x^2=k (mod n) for (k,n)=1 and assuming solvability.
formula: a(n) = A005087(n) + i, where i may be 0, 1 or 2 according as 2^j divides n, respectively with j <= 1, j=2 or j>=3, (i.e. i=0 when n is not divisible by 4; i=1 when n is divisible by 4 but not by 8; i=2 when n is divisible by 8).

A072275.name: Least m such that one less than m-th prime has n divisors (or 0 if no such prime exists).

A072277.name: Smallest integer > 1 which is both n-gonal and centered n-gonal.

A072278.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) is the sum of the first k divisors of n for some k.

A072279.name: Dimension of n-th graded section of a certain Lie algebra.
formula: a(n) = (1/n) * Sum_{k|n} moebius(n/k) (t1^k + t2^k), where t1, t2 are the roots of x^2-4x+1.

A072280.name: Product representation of the Pell numbers A000129 and A002203.

A072281.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) + 1 and phi(n) - 1 are twin primes.

A072282.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) + 1 and sigma(n) - 1 are twin primes.

A072283.name: Number of raised dots to represent n in Braille.
formula: The decimal digits map to numbers of Braille raised dots as follows: 0 -> 3, 1 -> 1, 2 -> 2, 3 -> 2, 4 -> 3, 5 -> 2, 6 -> 3, 7 -> 4, 8 -> 3 and 9 -> 2.

A072284.name: Numbers k begins a new chain of squarefree integers. I.e., k is squarefree but k-1 is not.

A072285.name: Numerators of inverse unimodal analog of binomial coefficients: binomial(n,m) = Sum_{k=0..n-m} a(2*k+m-1, 2*k).
formula: a(n, m) = binomial(n-m/2+1, n-m+1) - binomial(n-m/2, n-m+1).

A072286.name: Denominators of inverse unimodal analog of binomial coefficients: binomial(n,m) = Sum_{k=0..n-m} a(2*k+m-1, 2*k).
formula: a(n, m) = binomial(n-m/2+1, n-m+1) - binomial(n-m/2, n-m+1).

A072287.name: Let f(n, m) = binomial(n - m/2 + 1, n - m + 1) - binomial(n - m/2, n - m + 1) and let s(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} f(n, k); then a(n) = numerator of s(n).

A072288.name: Smallest prime factor of Googolplex + n which exceeds 16.

A072289.name: One eighty-fourth the area of primitive Pythagorean triangles with (increasing) square hypotenuses (precisely those of A008846).

A072290.name: Number of digits in the decimal expansion of the Champernowne constant that must be scanned to encounter all n-digit strings.

A072292.name: Number of proper powers b^d <= n (b > 1, d > 1).

A072294.name: Areas of primitive Heronian triangles sorted by longest side, then by middle side and finally shortest side.

A072296.name: Least number starting a chain of exactly n consecutive even integers that do not have cototient-inverses.

A072297.name: Number of even non-cototients not exceeding 2^n.

A072298.name: Smallest integer k such that for no integer m, m! is divisible by n^k but not by n^(k+1).

A072299.name: Reverse(n) is a prime factor of n.

A072300.name: Number of positive integers not exceeding n that are relatively prime to reverse(n).

A072301.name: Number of positive integers not exceeding n that are relatively prime to sigma(n).

A072302.name: Number of positive integers not exceeding n that are relatively prime to phi(n).

A072303.name: Numbers n for which n is congruent to n^2 mod phi(n).

A072304.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 0's.

A072305.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 1's.

A072306.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 2's.

A072307.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 3's.

A072308.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 4's.

A072309.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 5's.

A072310.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 6's.

A072311.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 7's.

A072312.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 8's.

A072313.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 9's.

A072314.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 9's.

A072315.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 8's.

A072316.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 7's.

A072317.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 6's.

A072318.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 5's.

A072319.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 4's.

A072320.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 3's.

A072321.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 2's.

A072322.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 1's.

A072323.name: Smallest Fibonacci number containing exactly n 0's.

A072324.name: Terms of A071383 such that A071383(n) = 5 * A071383(n-1).

A072325.name: Number of even numbers that cannot be expressed as the difference p-q of two odd primes q < p <= prime(n).

A072326.name: Conjectured values of n such that the sum of proper divisors of x*n is never prime for any x >= 1 (i.e., sigma(xn) - xn is never prime for x >= 1).

A072327.name: Numbers k such that k^2 is a term of A072510.

A072330.name: Common difference n such that primitive triangles exist which are n-arithmetic (i.e., primitive Heronian triangles whose sides in arithmetic progression have common difference n).
formula: n = 1 or a product of primes p congruent to +- 1 (mod 12).

A072332.name: Largest eigenvalue, rounded to the nearest integer, of a rank n matrix of 1..n^2 filled successively along antidiagonals (A069480).

A072333.name: Largest eigenvalue, rounded to the nearest integer, of a rank n matrix of 1..n^2 filled successively along rows.

A072335.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x^2)*(1-4*x+x^2)).
formula: The g.f. can also be written as 1/(1-4*x+4*x^3-x^4), which relates this sequence to the family of sequences described in A225682.

A072336.name: EULER transform of A064831 (with its initial 1 omitted).

A072337.name: Inverse EULER transform of A064831 (with its initial 1 omitted).
formula: G.f.: 1 + Sum_{s>=1} (mu(s)/s)*log B(x^s), where B(x) = 1/((1-x^2) * (1-3*x+x^2)). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Dec 03 2017

A072338.name: EULER transform of A002620 (with the initial 0,0,1 omitted).

A072339.name: Any number n can be written (in two ways, one with m even and one with m odd) in the form n = 2^k_1 - 2^k_2 + 2^k_3 - ... + 2^k_m where the signs alternate and k_1 > k_2 > k_3 > ... >k_m >= 0; sequence gives minimal value of m.
formula: Conjecture: a(n)=1 if n=2^k, a(n)=a(2^k-i)+1 if 2^k<n+i<2^(k+1). - John W. Layman, Jul 18 2002

A072340.name: Number of steps to reach an integer starting with n/3 and iterating the map x -> x*ceiling(x), or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A072341.name: a(n) = the least natural number k such that k*sigma(n) + 1 is prime.

A072342.name: a(n) = the least natural number k such that k*reverse(n) + 1 is prime.

A072344.name: a(n) = the least natural number k such that k*phi(n) + 1 is prime.

A072345.name: Volume of n-dimensional sphere of radius r is V_n*r^n = Pi^(n/2)*r^n/(n/2)! = C_n*Pi^floor(n/2)*r^n; sequence gives numerator of C_n.
formula: 1 if n even, 2^((n+1)/2) if n odd.

A072346.name: Volume of n-dimensional sphere of radius r is V_n*r^n = Pi^(n/2)*r^n/(n/2)! = C_n*Pi^floor(n/2)*r^n; sequence gives denominator of C_n.
formula: (n/2)! if n even, n!! if n odd.

A072347.name: If n = pqr...st in binary, a(n) = value of continuant [p,q,r,...,s,t].
formula: Hence this sequence is 2-regular in the sense of Allouche and Shallit (1992). - _Jeffrey Shallit_, Oct 13 2017

A072348.name: Number of primes whose decimal representation has the form rns where r and s are single digits.

A072349.name: a(n) = m such that A064388(m) = n, or 0 if no such m exists.

A072350.name: E.g.f. A(x) satisfies A(A(x)) = tan(x), where A(x) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^(2n-1)/(2n-1)!.
formula: a(n)=(2*n-1)!*T(2*n-1,1), T(n,k)=if n=k then 1 else 1/2*(T059419(n,k)*k!/n!-sum(i=k+1..n-1, T(n,i)*T(i,k))). [From Vladimir Kruchinin, Nov 11 2011]

A072351.name: Smallest n-digit Fibonacci number.
formula: A072351(n) = floor(1/2 + phi^ceiling((n*log(10) + (1/2)*log(5))/log(phi))/sqrt(5)). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, May 27 2011

A072353.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the largest Fibonacci number containing n digits.

A072354.name: a(n)-th Fibonacci number is the smallest Fibonacci number containing n digits.
formula: For n>1, a(n) = floor(n*c) (+3) or (+2) where c=log(10)/log(Phi) and Phi is the golden ratio = (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 21 2002
For n>1, a(n) = A072353(n-1) + 1. - _Michel Marcus_, Jun 01 2014

A072355.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k) = (Pi^2)*(k/6) rounded off (where 0.5 is rounded to 0).

A072356.name: a(n) = if n=p*q^2 for primes p<>q then q*p^2 else n.

A072357.name: Cubefree nonsquares whose factorization into a product of primes contains exactly one square.

A072358.name: Number of cubefree numbers <= n which are not squarefree.

A072359.name: Primes p such that the p-1 digits of the decimal expansion of k/p (for k=1,2,3,...,p-1) fit into the k-th row of a magic square grid of order p-1.

A072360.name: One-sixth the area of the smallest primitive d-arithmetic triangle, where d=A072330(n).
formula: a(n) = x'*y'/2, where (x', y') is the fundamental solution to x^2 - 3*y^2 = d^2, where d=A072330(n).

A072361.name: Number of vertically indecomposable distributive lattices on n nodes.

A072362.name: Composite numbers whose sum of aliquot divisors is palindromic.

A072363.name: Composite numbers whose sum of divisors is palindromic.

A072366.name: Numbers x such that x + reverse of x is a prime.

A072367.name: Squares x such that x + reverse of x is a prime.

A072368.name: Minimal total volume of n bricks with integer sides, all sides being different. Lowest value of sum of products of triples p*q*r chosen from [1,3n].

A072369.name: Cubes x such that x + reverse of x is a prime.

A072370.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) = log(n) + 2 * EulerGamma - 1 (rounded off), where tau(n) denotes the number of divisors of n and EulerGamma denotes the Euler-Mascheroni constant (0.5 is rounded to 0).

A072373.name: Complexity of doubled cycle (regarding case n = 2 as a graph).

A072374.name: a(1) = 1; a(n) = 1 + Sum_{i=1..n} Product_{j=i..2*i-1} (n-j).
formula: The sequence 1, 1, 2, 3, .. has a(n)=sum{k=0..floor(n/2), C(n-k, k)k!} (diagonal sums of permutation triangle A008279). - _Paul Barry_, May 12 2004

A072375.name: Number of cubefree numbers <= n which are nonsquares having exactly one square in their factorization.
formula: a(n) ~ c * n, where c = (6/Pi^2) * Sum_{p prime} 1/(p*(p+1)) = 0.200755... (A271971). - _Amiram Eldar_, Feb 16 2021

A072376.name: a(n) = a(floor(n/2)) + a(floor(n/4)) + a(floor(n/8)) + ... starting with a(0)=0 and a(1)=1.

A072377.name: Number of pairs of orthogonal Latin squares of order n.

A072378.name: Numbers n such that 12*n divides F(12*n), where F(m) is the m-th Fibonacci number.

A072379.name: Sum_{k<=n} (sigma(k)^2), where sigma(k) denotes the sum of the divisors of k A000203.

A072380.name: Third differences of partition numbers A000041.
formula: a(n) ~ exp(Pi*sqrt(2*n/3)) * Pi^3 / (72 * sqrt(2) * n^(5/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 06 2017

A072381.name: Numbers m such that Fibonacci(m) is a semiprime.

A072382.name: Primes which can be represented as the sum of a number and its reverse.

A072383.name: Primes which can be represented as the sum of a square and its reverse.

A072384.name: Primes which can be represented as the sum of a cube and its reverse.

A072385.name: Primes which can be represented as the sum of a prime and its reverse.

A072386.name: Primes which can be represented as the sum of a triangular number and its reverse.

A072387.name: Triangular number x such that x + reverse of x is a prime.

A072388.name: a(0) = 1; for n > 0, a(n) = floor((prime(n+1) + prime(n) + a(n-1))/3).

A072389.name: Numbers of the form x*(x+1) * y*(y+1) ("bipronics") with x and y nonnegative integers.

A072391.name: D2(n,n) = Sum_{1<=k<=n} (d_n(k^2)), where d_a(k^2)=card{d: d|k and 1<=d<=a} for real a.
formula: Asymptotic expression (includes error term): a(n)=(n*log(n)^2/(4*zeta(2)))+(n*log(n)/zeta(2))*((3*gamma/2)-(zeta'(2)/zeta(2)))+O(n), gamma = A001620.

A072392.name: Numbers n such that reverse(n) = phi(n) (mod n).

A072393.name: Numbers n such that n - reverse(n) = phi(n).

A072395.name: Numbers n such that reverse(phi(n)) = n.

A072396.name: Index of smallest Fibonacci number with n prime factors when counted with multiplicity.

A072397.name: Smallest Fibonacci number with n prime factors when counted with multiplicity.

A072398.name: Numerator of best approximation to Pi with denominator <= 10^n.

A072399.name: Denominator of best approximation to Pi with denominator <= 10^n.

A072401.name: 1 iff n is of the form 4^m*(8k+7).

A072402.name: a(n) = 6^n *sum_{k=1..infinity} Gamma(n+k/6)/ (k!*Gamma(k/6) *exp(1)), where Gamma is Capital-Greek-Gamma, the Gamma-function.

A072403.name: Numerator of the Reingold-Tarjan sequence, denominator=A072404.

A072404.name: Denominator of the Reingold-Tarjan sequence, numerator=A072403.

A072405.name: Triangle T(n, k) = C(n,k) - C(n-2,k-1) for n >= 3 and T(n, k) = 1 otherwise, read by rows.
formula: T(n, k) = C(n,k) - C(n-2,k-1) for n >= 3 and T(n, k) = 1 otherwise.
T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + T(n-1, k) starting with T(2, 0) = T(2, 1) = T(2, 2) = 1 and T(n, 0) = T(n, n) = 1.
T(n, k, q) = q*[n=2] + Sum_{j=0..5} q^j*binomial(n-2*j, k-j)*[n>2*j] with T(n,0) = T(n,n) = 1 for q = -1. (End)

A072406.name: Number of values of k for which C(n,k)-C(n-2,k-1) is odd.

A072408.name: Least number > 1 which equals n-th power of the sum of its digits in decimal base.

A072409.name: 4th-order digital invariants: the sum of the 4th power of the digits of n equals some number k and the sum of the 4th power of the digits of k equals n.

A072410.name: Number of iterations of the map k -> A000001(k) needed to reach 1 starting at n, or -1 if no such number exists.

A072411.name: LCM of exponents in prime factorization of n, a(1) = 1.
formula: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = lcm(A067029(n), a(A028234(n)). - _Antti Karttunen_, Aug 09 2016

A072412.name: Numbers k such that the LCM of exponents in the prime factorization of k does not equal the largest exponent.

A072413.name: Numbers k such that the LCM of exponents in the prime factorization of k does not equal the product of the exponents.

A072414.name: Non-Achilles numbers for which LCM of the exponents in the prime factorization of n is not equal to the maximum of the same exponents.
formula: A051903(a(n)) is not equal A072411(a(n)) but the numbers are not in A052486.

A072415.name: a(1) = 2; a(n) = a(n-1)-th even nontotient number.
formula: a(3)=182 is the 26th = a(2)-th term in A005277.

A072416.name: a(1) = 2; a(n) = half of the a(n-1)-th even nontotient number.
formula: a(5) = 373 = 746/2, where 746 is the a(4) = 149th term in A005277.

A072417.name: a(n) = smallest positive m such that m! contains exactly n 0's, or 0 if no such m exists.

A072419.name: Smallest factorial containing exactly n 0's, or 0 if no such factorial exists.

A072420.name: This sequence lists the "toscodicity" of the integers, the minimum number of steps needed to transform the integer into 153 (which happens to be the sum of the cube of its digits, the sum of the first 17 integers and fishily "happens" to be the number of fish mentioned in John 21:10) by the TOSCOD (triple or sum cubes of digits) operator.
formula: By applying the proper combination of the two alternative operations one minimum number of operations can be determined.

A072421.name: The p-est sequence is similar to the Aronson sequence except that instead of the generating sentence beginning with T, it begins with P and instead of being in English it is in Latin.
formula: From the generating sentence: "p est prima praeterea quinta praeterea decima praeterea quinta vicesima praeterea quadragesima praeterea tertia sexagesima praeterea quarta octogesima praeterea decima centesima ... littera in hic sententiam."

A072422.name: The n-est sequence is similar to the Aronson sequence except that instead of the generating sentence beginning with T, it begins with N and instead of being in English it is in Latin.
formula: From the generating sentence: "N est prima littera in hic sententiam, doudevicesima littera in hic sententiam, quarta vicesima littera in hic sententiam, septima vicesima littera in hic sententiam, tertia quinquagentesima littera in hic sententiam ...."

A072423.name: The t-est sequence is similar to the Aronson sequence except that instead of being in English it is in Latin.
formula: From the generating sentence: "T est prima et quarta et undecima et sexima decima et nona decima et nona vicesima ... littera in hic sententiam."

A072424.name: The five's sequence merely counts the letters in the words of the generating sentence.
formula: From the generating sentence: "Five's the number of letters in the first word of this sentence, three in the second, six in the third, two in the fourth, three in the fifth ..."

A072425.name: The four-is sequence merely counts the letters in the words of the generating sentence.
formula: From the generating sentence: "Four is the number of letters in the first word of this sentence, two in the second, three in the third, six in the fourth, two in the fifth ..."

A072426.name: Numbers whose Hebrew name begin with the letter "Shin".

A072427.name: Numbers n for which there is a unique k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072428.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly four k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072429.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly five k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072430.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly six k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072431.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly seven k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072432.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly eight k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072433.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly nine k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072434.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly ten k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072435.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly twelve k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A072436.name: Remove prime factors of form 4*k+3.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p) = (if p==3 (mod 4) then 1 else p).

A072437.name: Numbers with no prime factors of form 4*k+3.
formula: n>0 such that A001842(n)=0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 24 2003

A072438.name: Remove prime factors of form 4*k+1.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p)=(if p==1 (mod 4) then 1 else p).

A072439.name: Primes prime(k) such that the number of binary 1's in prime(k) equals the number of binary 1's in k.

A072440.name: Number of 3-smooth numbers with decimal digits <= 3.

A072441.name: Least k such that Sum( Sin(1/Sqrt(i)) i=1..k) > n.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to n^2/4. Does lim n -> infinity ABS(4*a(n)-(n+1)^2)/n exist? - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 16 2002

A072442.name: Least k such that Sum( Cos(1/Sqrt(i)) i=1..k) > n.

A072443.name: Nonsquares which are the product of two numbers with the same digits (leading zeros are forbidden).

A072444.name: Number of subsets S of the power set P{1,2,...,n} such that: {1}, {2},..., {n} are all elements of S; if X and Y are elements of S and X and Y have a nonempty intersection, then the union of X and Y is an element of S. The sets S are counted modulo permutations on the elements 1,2,...,n.

A072445.name: Number of subsets S of the power set P{1,2,...,n} such that: {1}, {2},..., {n} are all elements of S; {1,2,...,n} is an element of S; if X and Y are elements of S and X and Y have a nonempty intersection, then the union of X and Y is an element of S. The sets S are counted modulo permutations on the elements 1,2,...,n.

A072446.name: Number of subsets S of the power set P{1,2,...,n} such that: {1}, {2},..., {n} are all elements of S; if X and Y are elements of S and X and Y have a nonempty intersection, then the union of X and Y is an element of S.

A072447.name: Number of subsets S of the power set P{1,2,...,n} such that: {1}, {2},..., {n} are all elements of S; {1,2,...n} is an element of S; if X and Y are elements of S and X and Y have a nonempty intersection, then the union of X and Y is an element of S.

A072448.name: Squares of the terms of the decimal expansion of Pi.

A072449.name: Decimal expansion of the limit of the nested radical sqrt(1 + sqrt(2 + sqrt(3 + sqrt(4 + ... )))).

A072450.name: Continued fraction expansion of the limit of a nested radical, sqrt(1 + sqrt(2 + sqrt(3 + sqrt(4 + ... )))).

A072451.name: Number of odd terms in the reduced residue system of 2*n-1.
formula: a(1) = 1, and for n>1 a(n) = phi(2n-1)/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 11 2002
It would appear that a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} abs(Jacobi(k, 2n-2k+1)). - _Paul Barry_, Jul 20 2005

A072454.name: Count of all nontotients in the reduced residue system of 2n-1.

A072455.name: Count of all totients in the reduced residue system of 2n-1.

A072457.name: Shadow transform of tetrahedral numbers A000292.

A072458.name: Shadow transform of Catalan numbers A000108.

A072459.name: Largest prime divisor of even nontotients.

A072460.name: Smallest even nontotient number of which the largest prime divisor equals n-th prime.

A072463.name: Shadow transform of sigma(n), A000203, starting with 0, sigma(1), sigma(2), ...

A072464.name: Code word lengths for non-redundant MML code for positive integers.

A072465.name: A Fibonacci-like model in which each pair of rabbits dies after the birth of their 4th litter: a(n) = a(n-2) + a(n-3) + a(n-4) + a(n-5).

A072466.name: Numbers with 11 odd integers in their Collatz (or 3x+1) trajectory.

A072467.name: Triangle in which n-th row contains n primes == 1 mod (n) and the first term of a row is just greater than the last term of the previous row.

A072468.name: Leading diagonal of triangle in A072467.

A072469.name: Right diagonal of triangle in A072467.

A072470.name: a(0) = 0, a(1) = 9; for n > 1 a(n) = smallest positive square (possibly required to be greater than a(n-1)?) such that a(0) + a(1) + ... + a(n) is a square.
formula: a(n) = A018929(n+1) - A018929(n) for n > 1. - _César Aguilera_, Nov 10 2018

A072471.name: Squares such that the sum of two neighboring term is also a square.

A072472.name: a(-1)=1, a(0) = 2; a(n) = product of numbers from p(n)+1 up to p(n+1), where p(n) is the n-th prime.

A072475.name: Sum of next n composite numbers.

A072476.name: Difference between the sum of first n prime numbers and the sum of first n composite numbers.

A072478.name: Surface area of n-dimensional sphere of radius r is n*V_n*r^(n-1) = n*Pi^(n/2)*r^(n-1)/(n/2)! = S_n*Pi^floor(n/2)*r^(n-1); sequence gives numerator of S_n.

A072479.name: Surface area of n-dimensional sphere of radius r is n*V_n*r^(n-1) = n*Pi^(n/2)*r^(n-1)/(n/2)! = S_n*Pi^floor(n/2)*r^(n-1); sequence gives denominator of S_n.

A072482.name: Partition the nonnegative integers into minimal groups whose sums are palindromes; this sequence gives the sums.

A072483.name: Triangle read by rows: The n-th row contains the smallest n increasing numbers larger than the last term of the previous row, which contain the string of digits of n.

A072484.name: Triangle in which the n-th row contains the n smallest numbers containing the string of digits of n in increasing order.
formula: T(n, k) = A293869(n, k) for any n > 0 and k = 1..n. - _Rémy Sigrist_, Jan 29 2021

A072485.name: n-th number that includes the substring [n] in its decimal expansion.

A072486.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = a(n-1) times smallest prime factor of n.

A072487.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = a(n-1) times largest nontrivial divisor if n is composite.

A072488.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = a(n-1) times largest divisor of n <= n^(1/2).

A072489.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = a(n-1) times smallest divisor of n >= n^(1/2).

A072490.name: Number of squarefree numbers (excluding 1) less than n.
formula: G.f.: (x/(1 - x)) * Sum_{k>=2} mu(k)^2*x^k. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Sep 14 2019

A072491.name: Define f(1) = 0. For n>=2, let f(n) = n - p where p is the largest prime <= n. a(n) = number of iterations of f to reach 0, starting from n.
formula: On Cramér's conjecture, a(n) = O(log* n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Feb 04 2013

A072492.name: Values of n for which A072491(n)=3.

A072493.name: a(1) = 1 and a(n) = ceiling((Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k))/3) for n >= 2.
formula: Conjecture: The constant c above equals (3/16)*K(4), where K(q) = C(q/(q-1)) (q > 1) is described in Odlyzko and Wilf (1991).
For a > 1, the constant C(a) = limit_{n -> infinity} f_n(a)/a^n, where f_{n+1}(a) = ceiling(a*f_n(a)) for n >= 0 and f_0(a) = 1.

A072494.name: First of triples of consecutive happy numbers, i.e., the first of three consecutive integers each of which is a happy number (A007770).

A072495.name: k-morphic numbers for any k such that (k-1)/10 is an even integer not divisible by 10.

A072496.name: k-morphic numbers for any k such that (k-1)/10 is an odd integer not divisible by 5.

A072497.name: Numbers n such that n^2 is member of A072498.

A072498.name: n is not equal to the product of the k smallest divisors of n for any k.

A072499.name: Product of divisors of n which are <= n^(1/2).

A072500.name: Product of divisors of n which are >= n^(1/2).

A072501.name: Ratio of the product of divisors of n which are > n^(1/2) to product of divisors of n which are < n^(1/2).

A072502.name: Numbers that are run sums (trapezoidal, the difference between two triangular numbers) in exactly 3 ways.

A072503.name: Number of ways to lace a shoe with n eyelet pairs such that there is no direct "horizontal" connection between any adjacent eyelet pair.

A072504.name: a(n) = LCM of divisors of n which are <= sqrt(n).

A072505.name: a(n) = n / (LCM of divisors of n which are <= sqrt(n)).
formula: If n = p^k for prime p, then a(n) = p^ceiling(k/2).
In particular, a(n) = n if and only if n is prime.
If n = p*q for primes p < q, then a(n) = q. (End)

A072506.name: Triangle giving T(n,m) = number of necklaces of two colors with 2n beads of which m=1..n are black.

A072507.name: Smallest start of n consecutive integers with n divisors, or 0 if no such number exists.

A072509.name: Number of Fibonacci numbers F(k) <= 10^n which end in 1.

A072510.name: Numbers n with property that n = product of first k divisors of n for some k.

A072511.name: Least number m such that 2m can be expressed as the sum of two distinct primes in exactly n ways.
formula: It seems that for n>7 n*log(n)*log(log(n)) < a(n) < 3n*log(n)*log(log(n)). Does lim n->infinity a(n)/n/log(n)/log(log(n)) exist ? - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 11 2002

A072512.name: Product of all n - d, where 1 < d < n and d is a divisor of n.

A072513.name: Product of all n - d, where d < n and d is a divisor of n.
formula: a(n) = (n-d_1)(n-d_2)...(n-d_k) where d_k is the largest divisor of n less than n (k = tau(n) - 1).
a(p) = p-1, a(pq) = pq(p-1)(q-1)(pq-1), p and q prime.
If n is not a prime or the square of a prime then n divides a(n).

A072514.name: Sum of n mod k for k in {1...n} with gcd(k,n) > 1.

A072516.name: Sum of remainders when n is divided by lesser squares.

A072517.name: Smallest triangular number beginning with the n-th triangular number other than itself.

A072518.name: Index of smallest triangular number beginning with the n-th triangular number other than itself.

A072519.name: Smallest Fibonacci number beginning with the n-th Fibonacci number other than itself.

A072520.name: Index of smallest Fibonacci number beginning with the n-th Fibonacci number other than itself.

A072521.name: a(1) = 6 and then the smallest triangular numbers such that sum of two neighbors is also a triangular number.

A072522.name: Smallest number a(n)>a(n-1) such that T(a(n-1))+T(a(n))=T(m) for some m, a(1)=3; T(i) are the triangular numbers.

A072523.name: Sum of remainders when n-th Fibonacci number is divided by all smaller Fibonacci numbers > 1.
formula: Conjecture: lim n->inf F(n)/a(n) = sqrt(5)/2 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number and therefore lim n->inf a(n)/a(n-1) = Phi (i.e. (sqrt(5)+1)/2 or lim n->inf F(n)/F(n-1)) - _Gerald McGarvey_, Jul 14 2004

A072524.name: Sum of the remainders when the n-th triangular number is divided by all smaller triangular numbers > 1.

A072525.name: a(0) = 1; a(n+1) is smallest composite number > a(n) such that a(n) + a(n+1) is prime.

A072526.name: Numerator of number J(n) arising in computation of second moment of A*_n lattice.

A072527.name: Number of values of k such that n divided by k leaves a remainder 3.
formula: a(n) = tau(n-3)-1 if n is congruent to {2, 4} mod 6, tau(n-3)-2 if n is congruent to {0, 1, 5} mod 6, tau(n-3)-3 if n is congruent to 3 mod 6; n<>3. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 06 2002

A072528.name: Table T(n,k) read by rows, giving number of occurrences of the remainder k when n is divided by i=1,2,3,...,n.
formula: Let a(m) be the m-th term in the sequence. Then m=f(n)+k where f(1)=1 and f(n+1)=f(n)+floor((n+1)/2). n is the number being divided by the various i's and k is the remainder under consideration. f(n) has the generating function F(x)= (x(1+2x^2-2x^3))/((1-x)^2(1+x^2)) - Bruce Corrigan (scentman(AT)myfamily.com), Oct 22 2002
G.f. for k-th column: Sum_{m>0} x^((k+1)*m+k)/(1-x^m). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 16 2002

A072529.name: Product of the next n multiples of n.

A072530.name: Number of primes p such that n divided by p leaves a prime remainder.

A072531.name: Number of primes p such that n divided by p leaves a 1 or a composite (nonzero) remainder.

A072532.name: a(0)=1; for n>0, a(n) = smallest prime of the form k*a(n-1)-1 with k>1.

A072533.name: Least Keith number (or repfigit) with n digits, or 0 if there is none.

A072534.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3 and a(n) = the smallest prime of the form k*a(n-1) - a(n-2).

A072535.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3 and a(n) = the smallest prime which is a linear combination of a(n-1) and a(n-2) of the form r*a(n-1) + s*a(n-2) with r,s >=1.

A072536.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3, a(3) = 5 and a(n) = the smallest prime which is a linear combination of previous three terms with all coefficients >=1.

A072537.name: a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3 and a(n) = the smallest prime which is a linear combination of all previous terms with all coefficients >= 1.
formula: For n >= 3, a(n) = A151800(S+(-1)^S) where S = Sum_{i=1..n-1} a(i). - _Robert Israel_, May 01 2019

A072540.name: Numbers that are not differences between successive Ulam numbers (A002858).

A072541.name: List of pairs of numbers (k, k+4), where k-1 and k+3 are primes.

A072542.name: a(n) = the least positive integer k such that sigma(k) > sigma(1) + ... + sigma(n).

A072543.name: Numbers whose largest decimal digit is also the initial digit.

A072544.name: Numbers whose smallest decimal digit is also the initial digit.

A072545.name: a(0) = 1, a(n) for n > 0 is the smallest number > a(n-1) such that a(n)-a(k) is nonprime for 0 <= k < n.

A072546.name: Sequence related to Fibonacci and "tribonacci" sequences : let f(1)=1, f(2)=n, f(k+2)=f(k+1)+f(k), t(1)=t(2)=t(3)=1, t(k+3)=t(k+2)+t(k+1)+t(k) (t(k)=A000213(k-1); sequence gives the smallest value k = a(n) such that t(k)>f(k).
formula: Asymptotically: a(n)= C*Log(n) + 0(Log(n)) with C a constant = 8.2... (this constant doesn't depend on initial values f(1), t(1), t(2), t(3) while f(2)=n )

A072547.name: Main diagonal of the array in which first column and row are filled alternatively with 1's or 0's and then T(i,j) = T(i-1,j) + T(i,j-1).
formula: If offset is 0, a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^(n-k)*binomial(n+k-1, k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 18 2003
G.f.: x*(1-x*C)/(1-2*x*C)/(1+x*C), where C = (1-sqrt(1-4*x))/(2*x) is g.f. for Catalan numbers (A000108). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 18 2003
a(n) = Sum_{j=0..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(2*n-2*j-4, n-3). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jan 28 2004
Other form of the G.f: f(z) = (2/(3*sqrt(1-4*z) -1 +4*z))*((1 -sqrt(1-4*z))/(2*z))^(-1). - _Richard Choulet_, Jan 25 2010

A072550.name: Number of Vice Presidents under n-th President of U.S.A.

A072552.name: Number of connected planar regular graphs of degree 4 with n nodes.

A072553.name: Sigma of n-th composite number equals a(n)-th composite number if it is also a composite or equals zero if sigma[c] is prime.

A072554.name: E24 range of preferred resistor values in electronic engineering.

A072555.name: Smallest of four consecutive integers divisible by four consecutive primes respectively.

A072556.name: Numbers n such that n and the n-th Fibonacci number have the same number of distinct prime factors.

A072557.name: Let w(n) be defined by the following recurrence: w(1)=w(2)=w(3)=1, w(n)=(w(n-1)*w(n-2)+(w(n-1)+w(n-2))/3) / w(n-3); sequence gives values of n such that w(n) is an integer.
formula: lim n -> infinity a(n)/n = 18/5. sequence contains numbers of form (5+18k), (11+18k), (16+18k), (17+18k), (18+18k) k>=0.

A072558.name: Decimal expansion of the one-ninth constant.

A072559.name: Continued fraction expansion of the One-ninth constant (A072558).

A072560.name: Denominators of w(n) where w(1)=w(2)=w(3)=1, w(n)=(w(n-1)*w(n-2)+(w(n-1)+w(n-2))/3) / w(n-3).

A072561.name: Denominators of w(n) equals 3 where w(1)=w(2)=w(3)=1, w(n)=(w(n-1)*w(n-2)+(w(n-1)+w(n-2))/3) / w(n-3).

A072562.name: Smallest of exactly n consecutive integers divisible respectively by the first n primes.
formula: If A069561(n+1) = A069561(n), then a(n) = A069561(n) + A002110(n). Otherwise, then a(n) = A069561(n). - _David Wasserman_, Oct 21 2004
a(n) = A069561(n) or A069561(n) + A002110(n), hence log a(n) << n log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jun 20 2015

A072564.name: Numbers m such that the absolute values of the real and imaginary part of zeta(1/2 + m*i) are both < 1.

A072565.name: a(n) = prime(n+1)*prime(n+2)+1 mod prime(n), where prime(n) is the n-th prime.
formula: a(n) = A023523(n+1) mod A000040(n). - _Michel Marcus_, Feb 28 2018

A072566.name: Numbers n such that n and sigma(n) end with the same digit in base 10.

A072567.name: Size of maximal set of points in an n X n (side length) grid such that no 4-set of it forms a rectangle with horizontal/vertical sides.
formula: a(n) = A001197(n) - 1 for n>=2. - _Rob Pratt_, Aug 09 2019

A072570.name: Even interprimes i = (p+q)/2 (where p, q are consecutive primes) such that (q-p)/2 is not divisible by 3.
formula: If  d = (P_{n+1} - P_n)/2 is even & d/2 == +/- 1 (mod 6), then P_n + d = (P_{n+1} + P_n)/2 is in the sequence. [Corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 29 2013]

A072571.name: Even interprimes i = (p+q)/2 (where p, q are consecutive primes) such that (q-p)/2 is divisible by 3.
formula: (P_n+1 - P_n)/2 is even but not divisible by 4.

A072574.name: Triangle T(n,k) of number of compositions (ordered partitions) of n into exactly k distinct parts, 1<=k<=n.
formula: T(n, k) = T(n-k, k)+k*T(n-k, k-1) [with T(n, 0)=1 if n=0 and 0 otherwise] = A000142(k)*A060016(n, k).

G.f.: sum(n>=0, n! * z^n * q^((n^2+n)/2) / prod(k=1..n, 1-q^k ) ), rows by powers of q, columns by powers of z; includes row 0 (drop term for n=0 for this triangle, see PARI code); setting z=1 gives g.f. for A032020. [_Joerg Arndt_, Oct 20 2012]

A072575.name: Triangle T(n,k) of number of compositions (ordered partitions) of n into distinct parts where largest part is exactly k, 1<=k<=n.

A072576.name: Limit of number of compositions (ordered partitions) of m into distinct parts where largest part is exactly m-n, for m sufficiently large given n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_k (k+1)! * A008289(n,k). - _Alois P. Heinz_, Dec 12 2012

A072577.name: Numbers n such that n and the n-th prime have the same number of 0's in their binary representation.

A072578.name: In binary representation: n has the same number of 0's as the n-th prime has 1's.

A072579.name: In binary representation: n has the same number of 1's as the n-th prime has 0's.

A072583.name: Numbers n with property that there is no match when comparing the 0's and the 1's of n and the n-th prime in their binary representations.

A072585.name: Numbers n such that n and phi(n) end with the same digit in base 10.

A072586.name: Number of numbers <= n having prime factors with odd exponents only.

A072587.name: Numbers having at least one prime factor with an even exponent.

A072588.name: Numbers having at least one prime factor with an odd and one with an even exponent.

A072589.name: n, phi(n) and sigma(n) end with the same digit.
formula: It seems that lim n -> infinity a(n)/n exists around 40.

A072590.name: Table T(n,k) giving number of spanning trees in complete bipartite graph K(n,k), read by antidiagonals.
formula: E.g.f.: A(x,y) - 1, where: A(x,y) = exp( x*exp( y*A(x,y) ) ) = Sum_{n>=0} Sum_{k=0..n} (n-k)^k * (k+1)^(n-k-1) * x^(n-k)/(n-k)! * y^k/k!. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 22 2019

A072591.name: In prime factorization of n replace multiplication with bitwise logical 'and'.

A072592.name: Even numbers with at least one prime factor of form 4*k+1.

A072593.name: In prime factorization of n replace multiplication with bitwise logical 'or'.

A072594.name: In prime factorization of n replace multiplication with bitwise logical 'xor'.

A072597.name: Expansion of 1/(exp(-x)-x) as exponential generating function.
formula: Recurrence : a(n+1) = 1 + sum { j=1, n, binomial(n, j)*a(j)*j } - _Jon Perry_, Apr 25 2005
E.g.f.: 1/(Q(0) - x) where Q(k) = 1 - x/(2*k+1 - x*(2*k+1)/(x - (2*k+2)/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 04 2013
a(n) ~ n!/((1+c)*c^(n+1)), where c = A030178 = LambertW(1) = 0.5671432904... - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jun 26 2013

A072599.name: Numbers n such that (n!)^2 - prime(n) is prime.

A072600.name: Numbers which in base 2 have fewer 0's than 1's.

A072601.name: Numbers which in base 2 have at least as many 1's as 0's.

A072602.name: Numbers such that in base 2 the number of 0's is >= the number of 1's.

A072603.name: Numbers which in base 2 have more 0's than 1's.

A072604.name: Last digit of n, phi(n) and sigma(n) is 0 in base 10.
formula: Does lim n -> infinity a(n)/n exist?

A072605.name: Number of necklaces with n beads over a n-ary alphabet {a1,a2,...,an} such that #(w,a1) >= #(w,a2) >= ... >= #(w,ak) >= 0, where #(w,x) counts the letters x in word w.
formula: a(n) = (1/n) * Sum_{d|n} phi(n/d) * A005651(d) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 25 2017

A072606.name: Number of pretzel (stellar or prismatic) knots and links.

A072607.name: If D[n] is divisor-set of n, then in set of 1+D only 2 primes occur:{2,3}; also n is not squarefree.

A072609.name: Changing of parity of remainder A072608(n) from alternation [..010101..] to steadily 1-range [...1111..]. AC-range corresponds to 0, while DC-range labeled by 1.

A072610.name: Values of transition of A072608(n) from alternating behavior (0,1,0,1,..) into steadily-1 (1,1,1,..) behavior or changing back. Expressing in terms of A072609(n): at n values it switches from steadily 0 into steadily 1 successive values or back.
formula: Value of n is such that A072609(n) is not equal A072609(n+1).

A072611.name: Numbers n such that phi(n) divides sigma(n+1)-sigma(n).
formula: Conjecture : lim n -> infinity Log(a(n))/Log(n) exists = 2, 6.......

A072612.name: Minimal value of { abs(n-sigma(k)) : k>0 }.
formula: Conjecture : S(n) = sum( k=1, n, a(k) ) = n + O(sqrt(n)) and more precisely for n large enough : n - (5/2)*sqrt(n) < S(n) < n - (3/2)*sqrt(n)

A072613.name: Number of numbers of the form p*q (p, q distinct primes) less than or equal to n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{p<sqrt(n)} (Pi(x/p)-Pi(p)), where Pi(n) is the prime counting function, A000720, and the sum is over all primes less than sqrt(n). [_N-E. Fahssi_, Mar 05 2009]
a(n) = Sum_{i<=n | Omega(i)=2} mu(i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jan 05 2013, revised May 25 2015
a(n) = Sum_{i<=n | tau(i)=4} mu(i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, May 25 2015

A072614.name: Sum( k = 1..n, (-1)^( n reduced mod k) ).

A072616.name: Number of essentially different ways of arranging numbers 1 through 2n around a circle so that the sum of each pair of adjacent numbers is prime and the odd (or even) numbers are in order.

A072617.name: Number of essentially different ways of arranging numbers 1 through 2n around a circle so that the sum of each pair of adjacent numbers is prime, with the odd and even numbers in order in opposite directions.

A072618.name: Numbers n for which the prime circle problem has a simple solution: the arrangement of numbers 1 through 2n around a circle is such that the sum of each pair of adjacent numbers is prime and the odd and even numbers are in order in opposite directions.

A072619.name: Permutation of natural numbers obtained from the permutation A072088 (zero-based).

A072620.name: Permutation of natural numbers obtained from the permutation A072089 (zero-based).

A072621.name: Permutation of natural numbers obtained from the permutation A072088 (one-based).

A072622.name: Permutation of natural numbers obtained from the permutation A072089 (one-based).

A072623.name: Numbers n such that A065863(n) = 1, i.e., prime(n) mod (n - Pi(n)) = 1.

A072627.name: Number of divisors d of n such that d-1 is prime.
formula: If p is prime <> 3, then divisors(p)-1 = {1,p}-1 = {0,p-1}, so a(p) = 0.

A072628.name: Number of divisors d of n such that d-1 is not prime.

A072630.name: Values of n where A072629 switches from 01010.. into 0000.. or back.
formula: a(n) = A000149(n) or A000149(n)-1 whichever is odd. [From _Max Alekseyev_, Feb 06 2010]

A072633.name: Smallest positive integer m where 1^n+2^n+3^n+...+m^n is greater than or equal to (m+1)^n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = 1 + round(n/log(2)). Formula verified for n=1..700. - _Herbert Kociemba_, Apr 08 2020

A072634.name: Permutation of natural numbers induced by reranking plane binary trees given in the standard lexicographic order (A014486) with an "arithmetic global ranking algorithm", using A054238 as the pairing function N X N -> N.

A072636.name: Permutation of natural numbers induced by reranking plane binary trees given in the standard lexicographic order (A014486) with an "arithmetic global ranking algorithm", using packA054238tr as the packing bijection N X N -> N.

A072638.name: Number of unary-binary rooted trees of height at most n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = A006894(n+1) - 1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 23 2007

A072640.name: Maximum position in A072660 where the value n occurs.

A072641.name: Binary widths of the terms of A072638.

A072642.name: Binary widths of the terms of A072640.

A072643.name: Half of the binary width of the terms of A014486, the number of digits in A063171(n)/2.

A072644.name: Size of the parenthesizations obtained with the global ranking/unranking scheme A072634-A072637.

A072645.name: Size of the parenthesizations obtained with the global ranking/unranking scheme A072646/A072647.

A072646.name: Composition of the permutations A048680 & A072636, i.e., a(n) = A048680(A072636(n)).

A072648.name: a(n) = [log_{Phi}(n*sqrt(5))], where log_{Phi} is logarithm in the base Phi ( = (sqrt(5)+1)/2) and [] stands for the floor function.

A072649.name: n occurs Fibonacci(n) times (cf. A000045).
formula: a(n) = floor(log_phi((sqrt(5)*n + sqrt(5*n^2+4))/2)) - 1, n >= 1, where phi is the golden ratio. Alternatively, a(n) = floor(arcsinh(sqrt(5)*n/2)/log(phi)) - 1. Also a(n) = A108852(n) - 2. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, May 02 2007
a(n) = -1 + floor( log_phi( (n+0.2)*sqrt(5) ) ), where log_phi(x) is the logarithm to the base (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 14 2007

A072650.name: Starting from the right (the least significant end) rewrite 0 to 0 and x1 to 1 in the binary expansion of n.

A072651.name: Table by antidiagonals used in calculating integer solutions to b^c=c^d with b,c,d>0.
formula: T(n, k)=n^(A052410(n)^k) if A052409(n)*A052410(n)^k/k is an integer [and with T(1, k)=1] but otherwise T(n, k)=0 if A052409(n)*A052410(n)^k/k is not an integer. b=n=r^m where r=A052410(n) is the smallest root of n and m=A052409(n) is the power of r that n is; c=r^k; and d=m*r^k/k providing this is an integer [while if n=1 then b=1, c=1 and d=k]. In effect, there is a solution if the largest divisor of k which is coprime to all powers of r is also a divisor of m.

A072652.name: Ordered solutions greater than 1 to b^c=c^d, with multiplicity.

A072653.name: Uniqued integer solutions n to n = b^c = c^d.

A072654.name: Maximum position in A072645 where the value n occurs.

A072655.name: Binary widths of the terms of A072654.

A072656.name: Permutation of natural numbers induced by reranking plane binary trees given in the standard lexicographic order (A014486) with an "arithmetic global ranking algorithm", using packA048680oA054238 as the packing bijection N X N -> N.

A072658.name: Permutation of natural numbers induced by reranking plane binary trees given in the standard lexicographic order (A014486) with an "arithmetic global ranking algorithm", using packA048680oA054238tr as the packing bijection N X N -> N.

A072660.name: Size of the parenthesizations obtained with the global ranking/unranking scheme A072656-A072659.

A072661.name: Composition of the A059905 and A048679, i.e., a(n) = A059905(A048679(n)).

A072662.name: Composition of the A059906 and A048679, i.e., a(n) = A059906(A048679(n)).

A072664.name: End of smallest run of n consecutive integers with n, n-1, ..., 1 distinct prime factors in that order.

A072665.name: Center of smallest run of 2n+1 consecutive numbers with exactly n+1,n,...,2,1,2,...,n,n+1 distinct prime factors, respectively.

A072666.name: Numbers n such that prime(n) + prime(n+1) - 1 is prime.

A072667.name: Consider m such that prime(m) + prime(m+1) = prime(k) + 1 for some k; sequence gives values of prime(m).

A072668.name: Numbers one less than composite numbers.

A072669.name: Primes of the form prime(x) + prime(x+1) - 1.

A072670.name: Number of ways to write n as i*j + i + j, 0 < i <= j.
formula: a(n) = p2(n+1), where p2(n) = (1/2)*(d(n) - 2 + ((-1)^(d(n)+1)+1)/2); d(n) is the number of divisors of n: A000005.

A072671.name: Least m which can be written as i*j+i+j in n different ways: A072670(m)=n.

A072675.name: Last digit of F(n) is 1 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: Sequence contains numbers of form (1+60k) (2+60k) (8+60k) (19+60k) (22+60k) (28+60k) (41+60k) (59+60k) k>=0.

A072676.name: Numbers n for which the prime circle problem has a solution composed of disjoint subsets: the arrangement of numbers 1 through 2n around a circle is such that the sum of each pair of adjacent numbers is prime, the odd numbers are in order and the even numbers are in groups of decreasing sequences.

A072677.name: a(n) = prime(prime(n)+1) where prime(k) is the k-th prime.

A072678.name: Generalized Bell numbers B_{4,2}.
formula: a(n) = (2*n)!*hypergeom([2*n+1], [3], 1)/(2*exp(1)), n=1, 2, ... Special values of the confluent hypergeometric function 1F1.

a(n) = sum(A090438(n, k), k=2..2*n)= sum((1/k!)*product(fallfac(k+(j-1)*(4-2), 2), j=1..n), k=1..infinity)/exp(1), n>=1. From eq.(9) of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=4, s=2. fallfac(n, m) := A008279(n, m) (falling factorials triangle). a(0) := 1 may be added.

A072679.name: a(n) = (3*(n-1)+3)! *(3*(n-1)+6)! *2F2(3*n+1,3*n+4; 4,7; 1)/( 3! *6! *exp(1)), where 2F2(;;) is the generalized hypergeometric series.

A072680.name: Difference between (least prime >= n) and (largest prime <= n).

A072682.name: Numbers congruent to {3, 36, 54, 57} mod 60.
formula: Sequence contains numbers of the form: 3+60k, 36+60k, 54+60k, 57+60k, k>=0.

A072683.name: Last digit of F(n) is 3 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: Sequence contains numbers of form (3+60k) (36+60k) (54+60k) (57+60k) k>=0.

A072685.name: Positive integers whose English names contain a prime number of letters.

A072686.name: Prime numbers whose (British) English names have a prime number of letters.

A072687.name: Number of primes with prime length names in range 1 -> 10^n.

A072688.name: Of the first n integers (inclusive), how many of them have a prime number of letters in their English names?
formula: a(n)=number of terms of A072685 <= n.

A072689.name: Difference between (least square >= n) and (largest square <= n).

A072691.name: Decimal expansion of Pi^2/12.
formula: Equals zeta(1,1), the double zeta-function with both arguments equal to 1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 10 2011
Equals Integral_{x=0..1} log((1+x^3)/(1-x^3))/x dx. - _Bruno Berselli_, May 13 2013
Equals lim_{n->infinity} A244583(n)/prime(n)^2. See A244583 for details. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jan 04 2015
Equals Sum_{k>=1} H(k)/(k*2^k), where H(k) = A001008(k)/A002805(k) is the k-th harmonic number. - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 20 2020
Equals Integral_{0..infinity} x/(exp(x) + 1) dx. See Abramowitz-Stegun, 23.2.8, for s=2, p. 801. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Sep 16 2020

A072692.name: Sum of sigma(j) for 1<=j<=10^n, where sigma(j) is the sum of the divisors of j.
formula: Asymptotic formula: a(n) ~ Pi^2/12 * 10^2n. See A072691 for Pi^2/12. Observe that A025281 also contains that constant in its asymptotic formula.

A072693.name: Special values of confluent hypergeometric function 1F1: a(n)=(5*n)!*hypergeom([5*n+1],[6],1)/(5!*exp(1)).

A072694.name: (p(n)#)^p(n), or n-th primorial raised to n-th prime power.
formula: a(n) = (p(n)#)^p(n), where p(n) is n-th prime and # denotes primorial (A002110).

A072695.name: a(n) = lcm(d(n^2),d(n)), where d(n) = A000005, the number of divisors of n.
formula: If n is squarefree product of k distinct primes, then a(n) = 6^k.
If n = p^2, then a(n) = 15, etc.

A072696.name: a(n) = lcm(d(n^3), d(n)), where d(n) = A000005, the number of divisors of n.

A072697.name: Squarefree numbers such that the sum of the prime factors is a multiple of the number of prime factors.

A072698.name: Sum of prime factors of A072697(n).

A072699.name: Number of prime factors of A072697(n).

A072701.name: Number of ways to write n as the arithmetic mean of a set of distinct primes.

A072702.name: Last digit of F(n) is 4 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A072703.name: Indices of Fibonacci numbers whose last digit is 5.

A072704.name: Triangle of number of weakly unimodal partitions/compositions of n into exactly k terms.
formula: G.f. with initial column 1, 0, 0, ...: 1 + Sum_{n>=1} (t*x^n / ( ( Product_{k=1..n-1} (1 - t*x^k)^2 ) * (1 - t*x^n) ) ). - _Joerg Arndt_, Oct 01 2017

A072705.name: Triangle of number of unimodal compositions of n into exactly k distinct terms.

A072706.name: Number of unimodal partitions/compositions of n into distinct terms.

A072707.name: Number of non-unimodal compositions of n into distinct terms.

A072708.name: Last digit of F(n) is 6 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A072709.name: Last digit of F(n) is 7 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A072710.name: Last digit of F(n) is 8 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A072711.name: Last digit of F(n) is 9 where F(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.

A072712.name: Primes p such that p divides the (right) concatenation of all numbers from 1 to p written in base 10 (most significant digit on left).

A072715.name: Record differences between n-th prime and 2n-th prime.

A072716.name: Integers expressible as (x^3 + y^3 + z^3)/xyz with positive integers x, y and z. (Alternatively, the integers expressible as x/y + y/z + z/x with positive integers x, y and z.)

A072717.name: Let d(k) be the sequence whose values are in (1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9) and are such that the continued fraction for the decimal number D(n)=0.d(1)d(2)...d(n) has strictly more elements than the continued fraction for D(n-1)=0.d(1)d(2)...d(n-1) and d(n) is as small as possible. Sequence gives values of d(n)=a(n) for d(1)=1.

A072718.name: Numbers n such that 12 applications of 'Reverse and Subtract' lead to n, whereas fewer than 12 applications do not lead to n.
formula: n = f^12(n), n <> f^k(n) for k < 12, where f: x -> |x - reverse(x)|.

A072719.name: Numbers n such that 17 applications of 'Reverse and Subtract' lead to n, whereas fewer than 17 applications do not lead to n.
formula: n = f^17(n), n <> f^k(n) for k < 17, where f: x -> |x - reverse(x)|.

A072720.name: Number of partitions of n into parts which are each powers of a single number (which may vary between partitions).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + A072721(n). a(p) = a(p-1)+1 for p prime.

A072721.name: Number of partitions of n into parts which are each positive powers of a single number >1 (which may vary between partitions).

A072722.name: Smallest of 6 consecutive integers divisible respectively by 6 consecutive primes.

A072723.name: Integers which are exactly the concatenation of the first m odd numbers (A019519) divided by their sum (A000290 = m^2).

A072724.name: Integers which are exactly the concatenation of the first m even numbers (A019520) divided by their sum (A002378 = m^2+m).

A072725.name: Integers which are exactly the concatenation of the first m numbers (A007908) divided by their sum (A000217 = m*(m+1)/2).

A072726.name: Numerator of the rationals >= 1 whose continued fractions consist of only even terms, in ascending order by the sum of the continued fraction terms and descending by lowest order continued fraction terms to highest.

A072727.name: Denominator of the rationals >= 1 whose continued fractions consist of only even terms, in ascending order by the sum of the continued fraction terms and descending by lowest order continued fraction terms to highest.
formula: a(n) = A072726(m) where m = n - floor(log_2(n)). a(0) = 0, a(2^k) = 1, a(2^k + 1) = 2, a(2^k - 1) = the k-th Pell number.

A072728.name: Numerator of rationals >= 1 whose continued fractions consist only of 1's and 2's, in ascending order by the sum of the continued fraction terms and descending by lowest order continued fraction terms to highest.
formula: a(F(n)+F(n-3)+m) = a(F(n-1)+m) + a(F(n-3)+m) when 0<m<=F(n-2), n>2; a(F(n)+m) = 2*a(F(n-2)+m) + a(F(n-4)+m) when 0<m<=F(n-3), n>3; where a(0)=1, a(F(n)-1) = F(n) = n-th Fibonacci number; a(F(2n-1)) = n-th Pell number.

A072729.name: Denominator of rationals >= 1 whose continued fractions consist only of 1's and 2's, in ascending order by the sum of the continued fraction terms and descending by lowest order continued fraction terms to highest.
formula: a(F(n)+F(n-3)+m) = a(F(n-1)+m) + a(F(n-3)+m) when 0<m<=F(n-2), n>2; a(F(n)+m) = 2*a(F(n-2)+m) + a(F(n-4)+m) when 0<m<=F(n-3), n>3; where a(0)=1, a(F(n+1)-1) = F(n) = n-th Fibonacci number; a(F(2n+1)) = n-th Pell number.

A072730.name: Smallest of 5 consecutive integers divisible respectively by 5 consecutive primes.

A072731.name: Difference of numbers of composite and prime numbers <= n.

A072732.name: Simple triangle-stretching N X N -> N bijection: push terms in the middle twice as far down to make space for the terms obtained by bisecting the edges, which are thus contracted by the same factor. Do this for all "triangle-shells" successively contained inside each other in A001477.

A072733.name: Simple triangle-stretching N X N -> N bijection: Inverse of A072732.

A072734.name: Simple triangle-stretching N X N -> N bijection, variant of A072732.

A072752.name: Maximum gap in one-stage prime-sieves.
formula: For n>=2 we define a(n) = max { m IN N | EXIST c(k) IN N, k=2, .., n : FOR ALL i IN {1, .., m} EXISTS j IN {2, .., n} : i == c(j) (mod prime(j)) }.

A072753.name: Maximum gap in two-stage prime-sieves.
formula: Let p(n) be the sequence of primes, i.e., p(1)=2. For n>=3 we define a(n) = max { m IN N | EXIST c(k), d(k) IN N, k=3, .., n : FOR ALL i IN {1, .., m} EXISTS j IN {3, .., n} : i == c(j) (mod p(j)) OR i == d(j) (mod p(j)) }

A072813.name: a(n)^A072814(n) is the n-th perfect power.

A072814.name: Smallest exponents of perfect powers: A001597(n)=A072813(n)^a(n).

A072815.name: Sum of proper divisors of 6n + 1.
formula: s(t(n)), where t(n)=6n + 1 and s(n) is the restricted divisor function.

A072816.name: a(n) is the smallest integer such that the mantissa of 1/a(n) contains n.

A072817.name: Accumulative sum of the greatest digit of n minus the least digit of n (A037904) <= 10^n.

A072818.name: Possibly the only integers of the form sqrt(m^2*(m^2-1)*2/3) [only checked for the first 5 terms].

A072829.name: Greatest m such that Product_{k=1..n-1} (1 - k/m) <= 1/2.

formula: It is known that 315^((n-1)/5) <= a(n) <= floor(n!*n*e). - Pierre Bornsztein (bornsztein(AT)voila.fr), Sep 02 2003
a(n) < A118771(n), and also a(n) <= A036918(n+1). - _Michel Marcus_, Mar 26 2013

A072844.name: Number of words of length 2n+1 generated by the two letters s and t that reduce to the identity 1 by using the relations sssssss=1, tt=1 and stst=1. The generators s and t along with the three relations generate the 14-element dihedral group D7.
formula: Empirical g.f.: x^4 / ((1 - 4*x)*(1 - 5*x + 6*x^2 - x^3)). - _Colin Barker_, Feb 24 2017

A072847.name: The a(n)-th highly-composite number (A002182) is the first one divisible by 2^n.

A072852.name: Number of permutations satisfying i-2<=p(i)<=i+5, i=1..n.

A072853.name: Number of permutations satisfying i-2<=p(i)<=i+6, i=1..n.

A072855.name: Number of permutations satisfying i-3<=p(i)<=i+5, i=1..n.

A072860.name: Highest power of 3 dividing the period length of 1/prime(n) = A002371(n).

A072861.name: a(n) = sigma(n)^2.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s)*zeta(s-1)^2*zeta(s-2)/zeta(2*s-2), Re(s)>3. - Antonio G. Astudillo (afg_astudillo(AT)hotmail.com), Jul 21 2002
Multiplicative with a(p^e) = ((p^(e+1)-1)/(p-1))^2. a(n) = Sum_{d|n} n/d*sigma(d^2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 30 2002
Equals the Dirichlet convolution of A065764 by A000027: a(n) = sigma(n^2) * n. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 02 2011

A072862.name: The smallest k>1 such that k divides sigma(k*n) is equal to 6.

A072864.name: Numbers n such that the smallest k dividing sigma(k*n^2) is equal to 3.

A072867.name: A Ramanujan congruence modulo 11^2 related to partition numbers: a(n) = p(121*n-5)/121 where p(k) is the k-th partition number.

A072868.name: Numbers n such that sigma(sigma(n)-n) = n.
formula: a(n) = 1 + A000668(n) (conjecture), which implies equivalent conjectures stated in A000668.

A072869.name: a(n) = sigma(sigma(n)-n), where sigma = A000203, sum of the divisors of n.
formula: For p prime, a(p) = 1. - _Michel Marcus_, Nov 19 2014

A072870.name: A Ramanujan congruence modulo 5^2 related to partition numbers: a(n) = p(25n+24)/25 where p(k) is the k-th partition number.

A072871.name: Smallest partition number divisible by n.

A072872.name: a(n) is the smallest positive number k such that n divides 2^k - k.

A072873.name: Numbers k such that Sum_i ( e(i)/p(i) ) is an integer, where the prime factorization of n is Product_i ( p(i)^e(i) ).
formula: A124010(a(n),k) mod A027748(a(n),k) = 0 for k = 1 .. A001221(a(n)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 21 2012

A072874.name: Numbers n such that A000213(n) == 1 (mod n).

A072875.name: Smallest start for a run of n consecutive numbers of which the i-th has exactly i prime factors.

A072876.name: a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = a(4) = 1 and a(n) = (a(n-1)*a(n-3) + a(n-2)^3)/a(n-4) for n >= 5.
formula: Lim_{n->infinity} (log(log a(n)))/n = log((1+sqrt(5))/2) or about 0.48. See A002390. However, convergence is extremely slow. - _Andrew Hone_, Nov 15 2005
a(n) = ceiling(e^(c0*phi^n + d0/phi^n)) if n is even,
ceiling(e^(c1*phi^n + d1/phi^n)) if n is odd,

A072877.name: a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = a(4) = 1; a(n) = (a(n-1)*a(n-3) + a(n-2)^4)/a(n-4).
formula: Lim_{n->infinity} (log(log(a(n))))/n = log(2+sqrt(3))/2 = A065918/2 or about 0.658. - _Andrew Hone_, Nov 15 2005; corrected by _Michel Marcus_, May 12 2019
a(n) = ceiling(e^(c0*x^n + d0/x^n)) if n is even,
ceiling(e^(c1*x^n + d1/x^n)) if n is odd,

A072878.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3) - a(n-4) with a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = a(4) = 1.
formula: From the recurrence a(n) = 4*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3) - a(n-4), any four successive terms satisfy the Markoff-Hurwitz equation a(n)^2 + a(n-1)^2 + a(n-2)^2 + a(n-3)^2 = 4*a(n)*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3), cf. A075276. As n tends to infinity, the limit of log(log(a(n)))/n is log x = 0.6093778633..., where x=1.839286755... is the real root of the cubic x^3 - x^2 - x - 1 = 0. - _Andrew Hone_, Nov 14 2005

A072879.name: a(n) = 5*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3)*a(n-4) - a(n-5) with a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = a(4) = a(5) = 1.
formula: From the recurrence a(n) = 5*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3)*a(n-4) - a(n-5), any five successive terms satisfy the five-variable Hurwitz equation a(n)^2+a(n-1)^2+a(n-2)^2+a(n-3)^2+a(n-4)^2 = 5*a(n)*a(n-1)*a(n-2)*a(n-3)*a(n-4). As n tends to infinity, the limit of log(log(a(n)))/n is log x = 0.6562559790..., where x=1.927561975... is the largest real root of the quartic x^4-x^3-x^2-x-1=0. - _Andrew Hone_, Nov 16 2005

A072881.name: a(1)=a(2)=a(3)=1; for n>3, a(n)=(a(n-1)*a(n-2)+a(n-1)+a(n-2))/a(n-3).
formula: Both sequences u=(a(2n-1))_{n>0} and u=(a(2n))_{n>0} satisfy the order 3 linear recursion : u(n)=14u(n-1)-14u(n-2)+u(n-3).
Sequences u=(a(2n)) and v=(a(2n-1)) satisfy order 2 linear recursions : u(n)=13*u(n-1)-u(n-2)-5 and v(n)=13*v(n-1)-v(n-2)-7. - _Bruno Langlois_, Aug 21 2016

A072882.name: A nonlinear recurrence of order 3: a(1)=a(2)=a(3)=1; a(n)=(a(n-1)+a(n-2))^2/a(n-3).

A072883.name: Least k >= 1 such that k^n + n is prime, or 0 if no such k exists.

formula: In blocks of 10 letters: saintthese condthirdf ourthfifth sixthseven theighthte nthelevent htwelfthth irteenthfo urteenthfi fteenthsix teenthseve nteentheig hteenthnin ...

A072891.name: The 5-cycle of the n => sigma(n)-n process, where sigma(n) is the sum of divisors of n (A000203).

A072892.name: The 4-cycle of the n => sigma(n)-n process. sigma(n) is the sum of divisors of n. (A000203) a(4+n)=a(n).

A072894.name: Let c(k) be defined as follows: c(1)=1, c(2)=n, c(k+2) = c(k+1)/2 + c(k)/2 if c(k+1) and c(k) have the same parity; c(k+2) = c(k+1)/2 + c(k)/2 + 1/2 otherwise; a(n) = limit_{ k -> infinity} c(k).

a(n) = A137515(n) + 1. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Feb 27 2013

A072896.name: 5th-order digital invariants: the sum of the 5th powers of the digits of n equals some number k and the sum of the 5th powers of the digits of k equals n.

A072897.name: Least n-th order digital invariant which is not an Armstrong number (A005188), or 0 if no such term exists.

formula: It seems that log(a(n)) is asymptotic to C*n*Log(n) with C=0.4....

A072899.name: Denominator of c(n) where c(0)=1 c(n+1) = n/c(n) + 1.
formula: It seems that log(a(n)) is asymptotic to C*n*Log(n) with C=0.4....

A072904.name: Nonsquares m such that the discriminant of the quadratic field Q(sqrt(m) ) < m.
formula: a(n) appears to be asymptotic to C*n with C=3.4.....

formula: sum(k=1, a(k)) is asymptotic to C*n with C=1.9091.....

formula: a(1)=1, a(2)=2; a(n+1)=2a(n)-a(n-1)+sod(a(n)) (sod = "sum of digits"). - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Oct 01 2009
Asymptotically it seems a(n)~c*n^2*log(n) for c~1.99... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 07 2009

A072923.name: Number of primes of the form floor( (1+1/k)^n ), 1<=k<=n.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) is asymptotic to C*n with C = 0.47......

A072924.name: Least k such that floor((1+1/k)^n) is prime.
formula: It seems that a(n)/sqrt(n) is bounded. More precisely for n large enough it seems that (1/2)*sqrt(n) < a(n) < 3*sqrt(n).

On the contrary, A.L. Whiteman conjectured that the sequence floor(r^n) for non-integer rational r > 1 always contains infinitely many primes.  If this conjecture is true for some r=1+1/k, then lim inf_{n -> infinity} a(n) is finite.  - _Robert Israel_, Jan 09 2018

A072925.name: Probably an erroneous version of A002845.

A072926.name: a(n) = sum( k = 1, n, A051699(k) ).
formula: Conjecture: a(n) is asymptotic to C*n*Log(n) with C=0.29......

A072927.name: a(n) = minimum value of abs(n-Phi(x)) x>0.
formula: a(A002202(n))=0 and it seems that sum(k=1, n, a(k)) is asymptotic to C*n*log(n) with C=0.15....

A072928.name: Let p_0(n) := the n-th prime number, taking the first prime number to be 2; p_[i+1](n) = p_i(p_i(n)); then a(n) := p_n(1).
formula: p_0(n) := the n-th prime number, taking the first prime number to be 2 p_[i+1](n) := p_i(p_i(n)) a(n) := p_n(1)

A072929.name: a(n) = Sum_{d dividing n} binomial(2d,d).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} C(2k, k)*x^k/(1-x^k). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 21 2003
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(binomial(2*k,k)/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 20 2018
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} C(2*gcd(n,k),gcd(n,k))/phi(n/gcd(n,k)) = Sum_{k=1..n} C(2*n/gcd(n,k),n/gcd(n,k))/phi(n/gcd(n,k)) where phi = A000010. - _Richard L. Ollerton_, May 19 2021

A072930.name: a(1)=1, a(2)=10, a(n) = floor(a(n-1)/Phi)+floor(a(n-2)/Phi) where Phi is the golden ratio (1+sqrt(5))/2 (if a(2) < 10 a(k) converges to an integer value).

formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..floor(n/2)} [Omega(i) == 2] * [Omega(n-i) == 2], where Omega = A001222 and [] is the Iverson Bracket. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 04 2018

A072933.name: Least k such that floor( (1+1/k)^n ) = floor( (1+1/n)^k ) is not equal to round(n*91/100).

formula: Note that it is not true that a(n+1)>2*a(n): 255 = a(8) < 2*a(7) = 2*169 = 338. - _Stefan Steinerberger_, Mar 14 2006

A072939.name: Define a sequence c depending on n by: c(1)=1 and c(2)=n; c(k+2) = (c(k+1) + c(k))/2 if c(k+1) and c(k) have the same parity; otherwise c(k+2)=abs(c(k+1)-2*c(k)); sequence gives values of n such that lim k -> infinity c(k) = infinity.

A072941.name: Least multiple of n having no prime gaps.

A073000.name: Decimal expansion of arctangent of 1/2.
formula: Define a pair of integer sequences A(n) = 4^n*(2*n + 1)!/n! and B(n) = A(n)*Sum_{k = 0..n} (-1)^k/((2*k + 1)*4^k). Both sequences satisfy the same second order recurrence equation u(n) = (12*n + 10)*u(n-1) + 16*(2*n - 1)^2*u(n-2). From this observation we obtain the continued fraction expansion 2*arctan(1/2) = 1 - 2/(24 + 16*3^2/(34 + 16*5^2/(46 + ... + 16*(2*n - 1)^2/((12*n + 10) + ...)))). See A002391, A105531 and A002162 for similar expansions.

Define a pair of integer sequences C(n) = 5^n*(2*n + 1)!/n! and D(n) = C(n)*Sum_{k = 0..n} (4/5)^k/((2*k + 1)*binomial(2*k,k)). Both sequences satisfy the same second order recurrence equation u(n) = (24*n + 10)*u(n-1) - 40*n*(2*n - 1)^2*u(n-2). From this observation we obtain the continued fraction expansion 5/2*arctan(1/2) = 1 + 4/(30 - 240/(58 - 600/(82 - ... - 40*n*(2*n - 1)/((24*n + 10) - ... )))).
Equals Integral_{x = 0..inf} exp(-2*x)*sin(x)/x dx. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 05 2019
